{{setTitle     "Tables"}}
{{setSubTitle  "Simple CSS for HTML tables."}}
{{setActiveNav "tables"}}

{{> header}}

<div class="content">

    {{sectionHeading "Default Table"}}
    <p>
        To style an HTML table, add the {{code "pure-table"}} classname. This class adds padding and borders to table elements, and emphasizes the header.
    </p>

    {{> tables/default}}

  {{#code}}
    {{> tables/default}}
  {{/code}}


    {{sectionHeading "Bordered Table"}}
    <p>
        To add horizontal and vertical borders to all cells, add the {{code "pure-table-bordered"}} classname to the {{code "<table>"}} element.
    </p>

    {{> tables/bordered}}

  {{#code}}
    {{> tables/bordered}}
  {{/code}}


    {{sectionHeading "Table with Horizontal Borders"}}
    <p>
        If you prefer horizontal lines only, add the {{code "pure-table-horizontal"}} classname to the {{code "<table>"}} element.
    </p>

    {{> tables/horizontal}}

  {{#code}}
    {{> tables/horizontal}}
  {{/code}}


    {{sectionHeading "Striped Table"}}
    <p>
        Large tables are easier to parse visually if rows are easily distinguishable. Adding the {{code "pure-table-odd"}} class name to every other {{code "<tr>"}} element changes the background of the row and creates a zebra-styled effect.
    </p>

    <p>
        <b>Note:</b> In browsers which support the CSS3 <a href="http://caniuse.com/#search=nth-child">{{code "nth-child"}} pseudo selector</a> a simpler approach can be used. The {{code "pure-table-striped"}} classname can be added to the {{code "<table>"}} element and the zebra-styled striping will happen automatically. This approach will <em>not</em> work in Internet Explorer 8 or lower.
    </p>

    {{> tables/striped}}

  {{#code}}
    {{> tables/striped}}
  {{/code}}
</div>
